<br>
Go somewhere and practice where you will not die if you get screwed up.  Find a newbie zone, pick 4 things, aggro them, practice rounding them up and snaring.  <br>
<br>
If you are like me and you play in first person mode, make sure you switch to a third person view so you can see how tightly packed they get. <br>
<br>
That really is the only hard part about quadding.<br>
<br>
Once you learn that, you will learn to deal with resists much easier.  Assuming you have 4 aggroed, lets say you get 2 resists.  The 2 snared ones are easy, just run and they wont catch you.  The other 2, just do the same thing you did the first time.  Run away until you get 5-6 out of range messages on your Flux Staff (if you dont have it, get it!) Then stop, pause a second, then cast snare.<br>
<br>
I normally just root park adds, then snare them too just in case.  Some wizards with Disintegrate just use that..i dont have it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
There is a great guide about quadding in the forums below but the one piece of advice i really strongly recommend is learning to quad somewhere that you wont die if you mess up.  Nothing is more disheartening than having to get rezzed all the time.<br>
<br>
Good luck!<br>
<br>
Master Garrath Moore<br>
